In Canada only Inuit are authorized to harvest bowhead whales. Inuit subsistence harvest removals are within approved levels. Management measures required for each bowhead harvest include:

a) A Bowhead Hunt Plan prepared by each host community in a given year, which has been approved by the corresponding Regional Wildlife Organization (Nunavut) or RNUK (Nunavik);
b) A DFO Marine Mammal Fishing License issued to the Bowhead Hunt Captains of hunts that have been approved by the appropriate RWO/RNUK; 
c) Gear restrictions to ensure public safety and humane harvest;
d) Harvest restrictions for calves and family groups; record keeping and harvest reporting.

The existing management plan is dated; DFO and the Inuit co-management organizations (Nunavut , Nunavik) are updating it to the Integrated Fisheries Management Plan (IFMP) format. 
DFO Science is developing a more detailed Precautionary Approach framework for subsistence marine mammal fisheries.
